^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Excellent declarer play. Let's discuss the play first.  I normally lead partner's suit, although with such good diamonds, I think a diamond lead is quite reasonable. Now let's count south's tricks:  2 diamonds, after the opening lead,  4 clubs, and 2 spades. South needs one more trick. |
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|She can establish a heart trick. The only fly in the ointment is if you lose the king of clubs, and a diamond comes back, she could end up losing lots of diamonds. But, as long as you duck a diamond once, and East who presumably has the ace of hearts, has 3 diamonds or less, you are fine. As East had a singleton, the diamond problem never materialized.|
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|marge did make one small error on defense. At trick 5 she should duck the low heart off dummy. She  established an extra heart trick for ginny by taking the ace. |
PG| ***** 26 ***** |


AT|
duffer66: Should I have led the jack for the opening lead?|
PG| ***** 27 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Yes, from your diamond holding, the J is better. For those who know about coded 10s and 9s, the 10 is the correct lead if that is what you play. Just briefly, if you play coded 10s and 9s (in NT only) you lead 10 from a broken sequence with J10, such as KJ10 or AJ10. Ssimilarly, 9 from broken sequence with 109, e.g. A109 K109 Q109. If you have J10 or 109, you lead the top. The advantage of that if you lead the J partner knows you have nothing higher.|
PG| ***** 28 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now to the bidding. Instead of 3N another possibility, if I want to be adventuresome is for me to pass 1H and hope partner reopens with a double. Note, a direct double by me is negative. Therefore, if I want to make a penalty double, I have to pass and hope partner reopens with a double. Anytime partner is short in overcalled suit(2 or fewer)--hearts here, they should reopen with a double.|
PG| ***** 29 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|In this case, 3N probably worked out best. However, the point I am trying to make is that it is important, when responder passes an overcall, for opener to try and make a reopening double with shortness in the overcalled suit.|
