^-|CS||CP||FP||
cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|First of all, let me define what I mean by a competitive auction.  A competitive auction occurs when each side has approximately the same number of points. Typically each side has somewhere between 17 and 23 HCP.  This scenario happens in a majority of the deals so it is very common. It may surprise you, but the single most important criteria for bidding in competitive auctions is the total number of trumps you have between the two hands.|
pg| ***** 244 ***** |


cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|The simplest way to explain this is that if you can figure out the number of trumps you have, you can safely bid the number of tricks equal to the number of trumps. For example, if you have 8 trumps between the 2 hands, you can safely bid to the 2 level.  Similarly, with 9 trumps, you can safely bid to the 3 level.  With 10 trumps, to the 4 level. BTW, this is why when Pard opens ONE of a major and you have 5 of his suit, you jump to 4 level.|
pg| ***** 245 ***** |


cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|This principle is based on what is known as the |
pg| ***** 246 ***** |


cp|8|at|"Law of Total Tricks"|
pg| ***** 247 ***** |


cp||at| and if you want a detailed explanation, Larry Cohen has written an excellent book about this law. Marty Bergen (yes the same guy who invented Bergen raises) has a couple of books entitled "Points Schmoints" which are particularly suited to beginners and intermediates. However,  the critical way you apply the law is how I explained it.  The more trump you have, the higher you can bid. |
